defaultUlster Bank believes there is a
default particular challenge in Northern Ireland around accessing venture capital that needs to be addressed. Northern Ireland’s banks, along with Government, have shouldered the role of financing most start-ups in the absence of significant equity funding. This 
defaultmay in part be due to the l
defaultimited opportunities for substantial V
defaultenture 
defaultC
defaultapital
default returns in a small
defaulter 
defaulteconomy
default dominated by the public sector and reliant on UK
default subvention. But there has also been a lack of ambition from local investors when it comes to developing
default V
defaultenture 
defaultC
defaultapital funded growth plans. This may be explained by 
defaulta lack of peer examples and an unwillingness to give up
default equity in family businesses. This
default cultural difference may also be a by-product of The Troubles
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Confederation of British Industry (CBI) acknowledged the problem in its ‘Getting Growth Finance Growing’ report last year. In a climate where bank lending to sustainable sectors
default 
defaulthas not st
defaultopped, the CBI said there needed to be greater access to private sources of capital. Northern Ireland is too dependent on bank and public financing and lags considerably behind other regions of the UK on equity financing which will be essential if the prov
defaultince is to develop the kind of first class knowledge economy the Stormont Executive is aiming for.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe CBI noted the British Venture Capital Association (BVCA) reported private equity accessed by its members in Northern Ireland fell from £163 million in 2
default010 to just £21 million in 2011. In Scotland, the BVCA’s members accessed £179 million in private equity in 2010 and £393 million respectively, while in Wales private equity accounted for £78 million and £127 million. 
default&#xa0;defaultLegacy Issuesdefault&#xa0;defaultUlster Bank is addres
defaultsing the issue of companies with problem debt – much of which is an overhang from the property boom on the island – through our Global Restructuring Group (GRG) which works with companies with debts of over £1 million and our Specialised Relationship Manag
defaulters (SRM) whose primary focus is to support SME customers with exposures under £1 million and help return their businesses back to good health. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn Northern Ireland, the bank has a legacy portfolio of £5.8 billion of primarily property related lending, ma
defaultnaged by a team of 143 GRG and SRM employees.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn all cases, both teams seek consensual solutions with customers on a case by case basis. 
defaultUnfortunately, it
default is not always possible to achieve agreement. In these circumstances, the bank has to take difficult 
defaultdecisions which may, regrettably, include the appointment of an insolvency practitioner. This is not a decision Ulster Bank takes lightly.
default&#xa0;
defaultOver the past 18 months, however, GRG has helped protect 5,500 jobs 
defaultand is on course to return £200 million of North
defaultern Ireland exposure across numerous trading businesses, to the mainstream bank during 2013. GRG has also provided approximately £50 million of additional finance to the Corporate and SME sector in NI to provide development and trading finance.
