defaultfunding 
defaultin the N
defaultorthern 
defaultI
defaultreland market
default since the launch of the scheme in 2009, accounting for 77% 
defaultof all financing 
defaultby value.
defaultUlster Bank believes EFG has an important role to play in accessing finance for new investment opportunities. The bank has suggested that Government should re-visit the 
defaultlevel of the net cap, increasing it to at least 33%. This would recognise the fundamental difference between Northern Ireland’s economy and the rest of the UK - Northern Ireland has a much greater reliance on the public sector and a preponderance of micro 
defaultbusinesses. Ulster Bank also believes Government should develop a co-ordinated marketing initiative with banks to promote EFG and should consider marketing and aligning the scheme to specific business sectors.
default6default. Lack of availability of detailed regional ldefaultending datadefaultWith regards to business lending, Ulster Bank completes a monthly Bank of England return through RBS 
defaultGroup 
defaultwhich shows our lending figures. However, one of the challenges in Northern Ireland is the lack of consistency in the definition of new l
defaultending across banks. For example, while Ulster Bank may not count renewals as a new loan, its competitors may count it. Therefore, if regional lending data is to be effective, there needs to be an agreed common definition of what constitutes new lending. 
defaultIn Northern Ireland, the British Bankers Association is working with banks and the Northern Ireland Executive on relevant data to inform the local business landscape. Whilst Ulster Bank is supportive of this principle, before committing to the publication,
default like the other banks, it will require assurances around data protection, customer confidentiality, consistency of definition and ensuring commercially sensitive information is secure. 
default7default.default Access to banking in rural communitiesdefault.
defaultUlster Bank recognise
defaults the importance many of its customers place in face to face contact with staff and it is cognisant of the important role branches play in the commercial heart of a community.
defaultHowever, throughout the world, banks – and other retail sectors – are witnessing
default significant changes in customer behaviour. More people are availing of online, telephone and mobile banking services and branch usage is declining. The trend is no different at Ulster Bank which is also witnessing a significant shift in customer behaviour
default. Customers now do more than twice as many transactions through new digital mobile phone and Internet banking channels as they do in branches.
defaultThis has meant Ulster Bank, like all UK, Irish and international banks, has had to adjust to changing customer ne
defaulteds and that has inevitably led to an ongoing review of our branch network. With 79 branches, Ulster Bank still has the largest branch network in Northern Ireland and is committed to continuing to provide branch banking services to personal and business cu
defaultstomers in both rural and urban locations. The bank has 246 free to use ATMs across Northern Ireland. In addition, current account customers (including basic account holders) are able to check their balance and withdraw cash from post offices. Ulster Bank 
defaultcustomers are able to use any branch to carry out their banking, not only their account holding branch. As result of the change in customer behaviour, Ulster Bank has since March 2013 made our Anytime Banking apps, Internet centre and contact centre availa
defaultble to SMEs. The contact centre has been operating 24 hours, seven days a week. 
defaultIn June 2013, Ulster Bank closed seven branches and four part-time sub offices in Northern Ireland. As a matter of course full due diligence will be carried out before we make
default any future decisions on specific branches.
default&#xa0;
defaultClosing any branch is never easy but in reaching a decision, Ulster Bank looks at its geographic branch coverage across the province and the proximity of other branches to the location being considered for closu
defaultre. Ulster Bank looks at customer numbers, footfall and the number of transactions going through an individual branch. Consideration – and engagement with relevant stakeholders – is also given in decision-making to the needs of specific customer groups – f
defaultor example, benefit recipients, vulnerable customers, elderly and young customers
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultDuring the recent branch closures, as part of Ulster Bank’s engagement with impacted customers, it
default wrote to its customers at least 12 weeks in advance to inform them that their branch
default was closing and to advise them of the details of their new branch including the nearest free to use ATM. During this process, branch managers also identified and met indi
defaultvidual vulnerable customers, so they could put in place steps that would meet those customers’ banking needs. Ulster Bank will replicate this approach for any future closures, and in addition, it will seek to strengthen its measures for vulnerable customer
defaults with an education programme to help them register and use our online, telephone and mobile banking services. This will include holding open master classes and individual customer meetings in branches in the period prior to closure to provide face-to-face
default support to help customers use Anytime Banking services.
default&#xa0;
defaultUlster Bank will also continue to ensure that, where possible, 
defaultstaff
default from branches that have closed are moved to other branches in their locality to maintain some continuity for customers who like t
defaulto see a familiar face in their branch.
default&#xa0;
defaultUlster Bank
default recognise
defaults
default 
defaultthat for some customers in rural locations, telephone or online banking
default is not a
defaultlways viable. To that end, the bank will be reintroducing in Northern Ireland a mobile banking van service to ext
defaultend face-to-face banking services to customers and communities where branches close. Ulster Bank will continue to give consideration to other inclusive services for our customers, particularly those in rural areas.
